    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1001"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1001">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.731/396</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 904]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 15, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 27</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that <persName
                        corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> has informed me that the search
                    which the censors are making to ascertain the reasons for stopping commercial
                    telegrams brings this result, <pb facs="0968" n="710" xml:id="pg_710"/> viz.,
                    that of 60 or 70 telegrams emanating from the United States and dated in
                    November or December, they find that only 3 were stopped by the British
                    censors.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Walter Hines Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
